for those interested, in Japanese the word for 4 is shi, and 7 is shichi, the word for death is also shi. the alternate words for the numbers are yon (4) and nana (7). because of the superstition they also avoid floors 4 and 7 in buildings, sometimes they go completely untouched

fun fact: Japanese actually has alternate words for their numbers 4 and 7 because the words sound very similar to their word for death and it creates superstition

i hope this gives people an idea of both sides of this discourse. you're welcome to form your own opinions of course, and if there's something you think i missed i'd be interested in hearing it

it's important to note that no one should be pressured into indicating their pronouns for reasons i listed above like not being out or questioning their gender, if we're forcing people to list their pronouns some are going to be forced to misgender themselves

the final one is to just create an inclusive environment for trans people, at work for example this could be wearing pronoun pins or putting pronouns in your email signature. this give people the opportunity to indicate their pronouns when and where they feel comfortable

another is to use they/them for everyone (and i do mean everyone not just people who's gender you feel unsure about assuming) until they offer their pronouns. this eliminates pressure from all parties to give their pronouns but there's the option to give their pronouns too

offering your pronouns first is a good one, it puts no pressure on the other person to give their pronouns if they're unsafe or unsure but it opens up the conversation for the other person to give their pronouns if they feel comfortable doing so

so, what's the solution to this issue? there's never gonna be one solution that all trans people are happy with, but i have seen some ideas that i think are a good middle ground so i'll share them below

asking EVERYONE their pronouns does break down those barriers of assuming gender/pronouns based on appearance, and for someone confused by the practice it opens up a conversation about trans and nonbinary identity

there's also a lot of trans people who pass as either a cis man or cis woman who use he/they or she/they pronouns and they like being given the opportunity to voice that they use both. by being asked their pronouns it indicates to them that they're in an accepting space

a lot of trans people however do like being asked their pronouns. for nonbinary people there's no visual indicator they can use to get people to assume their pronouns are they/them, let alone neopronouns, pronoun pins exist but they can make someone a target for harassment

another argument against it goes hand in hand with the danger aspect. by asking someone their pronouns if they're not out or questioning their gender they're forced to either misgender themself or out themselves when they're not ready and in front of someone who's transphobic

it ends up with people trying to find this delicate balance of not misgendering people but also not putting themselves in danger. this unfortunately is still flawed because a lot of people will be cis passing but not use the pronouns you would assume from appearances

i think however we also need to talk about why people only feel comfortable asking trans people for their pronouns. this was an effort created by our community, and as shown by a lot of the discourse around it, many cis people will get upset if you ask them their pronouns

it's been an unfortunate side effect of something originally well intentioned. a lot of people will only ask people they think are trans and it becomes something where instead of it being inclusive it ends up singling out trans people

i'm someone who personally doesn't like being asked pronouns, because in my personal experience it only ever happens when people find out i'm trans or before hormones when they suspected i'm trans. people don't like feeling like they've been clocked

a lot of passing binary trans people don't like being asked their pronouns because they feel like it should be obvious, and while this way of thinking is damaging to those who don't pass or don't conform to gender norms there are some other reasons they don't like being asked

the idea around asking for pronouns was to help trans people and encourage the idea that you can't assume pronouns based on physical appearance. in theory there's nothing wrong with this idea but a lot of trans people, both binary and nonbinary, have been speaking out against it

alright let's talk about the asking for pronouns discourse because there's good points on both sides of the argument. basically i'm gonna go over both sides and some potential solutions in this thread so here we go. while i have my own opinions i'll try to remain unbiased
